Veteran filmmaker and actor, Fred Amata has reminisced about how he dedicated his career to the Nigerian movie industry. Amata made this known in an exclusive interview with The Nation on his journey so far and what he has been up to.   Five Nigerian female celebrities who went from fat to fit     Eight Nigerian celebrities with traditional titles     A goat’s bleating made my birth easy, Bella Shmurda speaks…   “My entire career has been in Nollywood. I finished school in 1986 and by 1987, I was already directing a television programme called Ripples which was the first independent production in those days. I have been making films, writing, producing, growing the industry, and even went into administering one of the major deals in the industry. I have had quite a long career you know, it started from television from 1987 till about 1993, 1994, 1995, we were still doing television, by 1997, I’ve started winning the best actor award before we now went into the years 2000, it is a long list of movies I have done and a list of things we have achieved so it is not fair to ask me that question”. Read Also: White Money to make Nollywood debut with Pete Edochie, Jackie Appiah Announcing his plans for 2022, he said “This year we are working on a major production, I just want to remind Nigerians that there used to be one guy who used to be a fantastic director who did films like ‘Ijele,’ ‘Letter to a stranger,’ ‘Suicide mission,’ they are so many films that we have worked on that were big-time hits and we are going to make one this year.”